      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div class="content-section">
        <div class="content-label">Common Questions</div>
        <h2 class="content-h2">Frequently Asked <em>Questions</em></h2>
        <div class="faq-list" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">Can joint degeneration actually be reversed?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Complete reversal of established arthritis is not currently possible. However, the progression can be significantly slowed, inflammation reduced, and pain eliminated — allowing patients to live active, comfortable lives without surgery. PRP therapy has shown evidence of cartilage regeneration in early-stage arthritis. The goal is maximum function and minimum pain for as long as possible.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">At what stage of arthritis should I seek treatment?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">The earlier the better. Grade 1 and 2 arthritis responds best to non-surgical treatment — with the highest chance of slowing progression and maintaining function long-term. Grade 3 arthritis can still benefit significantly from injections and physiotherapy. Grade 4 (bone on bone) may still be managed conservatively in patients who are not surgical candidates. Do not wait until pain becomes unbearable.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">How is Dr. Sharma's approach different from a standard orthopaedic consultation?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Dr. Sarish Sharma relies primarily on clinical symptoms and examination findings rather than over-investigation. He does not recommend surgery as a default response to arthritis. Every patient receives a comprehensive, individualised non-surgical plan combining the most appropriate injection therapy, physiotherapy coordination, and lifestyle guidance — before surgery is ever considered.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">How long will non-surgical treatment keep me out of surgery?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">This varies widely based on age, arthritis severity, body weight, and treatment compliance. Many patients with mild to moderate arthritis are kept comfortable and functional for 5–10+ years with regular non-surgical management. Some avoid surgery entirely. The combination of viscosupplementation, PRP, physiotherapy, and lifestyle changes provides the best long-term outcomes.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false">
              <span itemprop="name">Do I need to bring my X-ray or MRI for the consultation?</span>
              <span class="faq-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-plus"></i></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
              <p itemprop="text">Bring any recent reports if you have them — they are helpful but not essential. Dr. Sarish Sharma's approach is clinical-first. He examines the patient thoroughly and can reach a diagnosis and treatment plan based on symptoms and examination findings alone in most cases. He will only request further investigations if genuinely needed — not as a routine.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>

